Florian, Gerhard, Jurgen, Kurt, Marliese, Wolfgang.","German (<b>Würth</b>): variant of   Wirth  . Compare   Wuerth  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wirth","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Kurt, Hans, Erwin, Gunter, Dieter, Ernst, Gerhard, Manfred, Reinhold, Armin, Erna.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): occupational name for an inn-keeper, Middle High German <i>wirt</i>, German <i>Wirt</i>.","German: status name for a man who was head of a family and master of his own household, from the same word in the sense ‘provider’."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Wourth was born in 1235, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, Richard de Plessitis, was 37 and his mother, Gladya de Romeyn, was 35. He had at least 1 son with Maude Withenych."},"et":{"1235–":"1235–Surnud","1235–Male":"1235–Surnud","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1198–Male":"1198–Surnud","1200–Female":"1200–Surnud","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","1198":"1198","1240":"1240","Bef 3 February 1270":"enne 3. veebruari 1270","1270":"1270","Southwick, Northampton, England":"Southwick, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1235–":"1235–Kuollut","1235–Male":"1235–Kuollut","1240–Female":"1240–Kuollut","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1198–Male":"1198–Kuollut","1200–Female":"1200–Kuollut","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","1198":"1198","1240":"1240","Bef 3 February 1270":"ennen vuotta 3. helmikuuta 1270","1270":"1270","Southwick, Northampton, England":"Southwick, Northamptonshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1235–":"1235–Décédé","1235–Male":"1235–Décédé","1240–Female":"1240–Décédée","1270–Male":"1270–Décédé","1198–Male":"1198–Décédé","1200–Female":"1200–Décédée","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","1198":"1198","1240":"1240","Bef 3 February 1270":"avant 3 février 1270","1270":"1270","Southwick, Northampton, England":"Southwick, Northamptonshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Richard Wourth est né en 1235, à Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, Richard de Plessitis, avait 37 ans et sa mère, Gladya de Romeyn, avait 35 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Maude Withenych."},"de":{"1235–":"1235–Verstorben","1235–Male":"1235–Verstorben","1240–Female":"1240–Verstorben","1270–Male":"1270–Verstor